my_collections.title: Objects Tagged as "Red Arcs"
my_collections.description: Galaxies can look red either because they are very dusty (often because they are forming stars very vigorously) or because they are a very long way away (and "redshifted"). #redarcs would be interesting either way! Let's see if we can find some.

my_collections.title: Buried Rings
my_collections.description: Some of the toughest lenses to spot! Key features are: a biggish bright yellow galaxy, with a circular ring of different-coloured light around it that is blended with the yellow galaxy starlight. These rings will be rare, but they are real gems: the fact that the lensed feature is a ring means that the source is being highly magnified, and that there is a *lot* of information about the mass distribution of the lens galaxy.

comment.body: You know how in Facebook you can click "Like" on all the posts and comments? Well I would be doing that on this thread if I could :-)  Anyway, IR gurus Aprajita and Jim now reckon zs = 2 is a better estimate for ASW0009io9,  so you should go with that for now. Sorry, astronomical uncertainty is an issue, I know :-)
I guess ASW0009l59 also looks quite spherical - I like the double model! :-)
Sorry, I forgot to say: all my comments refer to ASW0009io9. One more: the lens galaxy does look very spherical, which does make the double configuration more plausible.
Also, nice work :-)

The SDSS lens redshift is 0.202. Also, @aprajita and @jgeach are tracking down other datasets at longer wavelengths to get an idea of the spectral energy distribution, and Aprajita reckons the source is probably around 4(!) It's pretty uncertain, but I'd go with that for now. 

Also, have you tried modelling it as a quad? it's such a long arc, is all. I haven't looked in Tools to see whether there are slight peaks in the arc, but that could help us decide on the double vs quad issue.
Try a hard browser refresh? I bet there are some odd errors hanging around after the server meltdown... :-)

comment.body: Hmm - I can't reproduce this, it all seems fine to me. Maybe try refreshing your browser hard? I suspect this was a side-effect of our server meltdown just after launch...

Hi there! Welcome to Space Warps :-) If you'd like to read a bit more about the images you're looking at, check out the [Space Warps blog](http://blog.spacewarps.org/2014/01/07/new-year-new-data-hunting-for-lenses-in-the-infrared-with-vics82/). There's also information there about how we designed the site, and what we found in our first project (in the optical, where lenses are slightly different colours but the same shapes. Have fun!

The site has turned orange! That means the refinement task has begun. The [blog post](http://blog.spacewarps.org/2013/11/22/coming-soon-narrowing-down-the-candidate-list-with-space-warps-refine/) has some explanation of what we're trying to do here, but feel free to ask questions below. Stay skeptical, people!

New blog post, [check it out!](http://blog.spacewarps.org/2013/11/22/coming-soon-narrowing-down-the-candidate-list-with-space-warps-refine/). We're getting very close - maybe 100k classifications - away from completing the CFHTLS dataset. In this post, we explain what will happen next - we're going to try and refine 3300 candidates that you have identified into a shortlist of high probability systems, that we can all present to the astronomical community. One last classification push, and then we'll get to see what we've found so far!

comment.body:
@C_cld: Els set up her model with 5 conjugate points (green and cyan) marking out the arc - I thought these were taken by SpaghettiLens to be the positions of the multiple images of a background point source, no? The synthetic image is made (I hope) by putting a small extended surface brightness distribution in the source plane and then mapping this into the image plane using the deflection angle maps - although given the offsets between input points and output synimage, I'm afraid that last part might not be true... 

Hello @Star_hunter_1! :-)

response_to.body:
This is an interesting model: 5 merging images would imply a rare "higher-order catastrophe" configuration, which are famous for providing very high magnification. I would love to know how much the source has been magnified in this synthetic image! The area in the source plane in which you can put a source and get 5 images is typically very small, so  such lenses are expected to be rare - but then, the high magnification might make the system easier to observe so... Let's make a note of Els' model while going back to the more common (and so more likely) 3-image arcs!

PS. @rafael_kueng, any idea why the conjugate image points not match the peaks of the synethetic image brightness distribution? It doesn't look like  a simple pixel offset bug...

On a more serious note : [9988](http://mite.physik.uzh.ch/data/009988)

Contour map and mass distribution look a bit iffy

![enter image description here](http://mite.physik.uzh.ch/result/009988/img3_ipol.png)
